13 We departed and climbed up the stairs
14 that the blind man had made earlier to descend,
15 my leader remounted and pulled me up;

22 so that it does not run without virtue to guide it;
23 so that, if a good star or a better thing
24 has given me the good fortune that I have remained steadfast, I do not begrudge it to myself.

46 And the leader, who saw me so intent,
47 said: "Within the fires are the spirits;
48 each one wraps himself in that by which he is burned."

55 He replied to me: "Within there Ulysses and Diomedes are tormented,
56 and thus together
57 they go to vengeance as they did to wrath;

67 "do not refuse to wait
68 until the horned flame comes here;
69 see how I bend with desire toward it!".

70 And he to me: "Your request is worthy
71 of much praise, and therefore I accept it;
72 but see that your tongue is restrained.

85 The greater horn of the ancient flame
86 began to shake itself, murmuring,
87 just like one that the wind torments;

97 could conquer within me the burning desire
98 that I had to become experienced in the world
99 and in human vices and valor;

109 so that man should not go any further;
110 on my right hand I left Seville,
111 on the other I had already left Ceuta.

121 With this short speech I made my companions
122 so eager for the journey
123 that I could hardly have held them back afterwards;

136 We rejoiced, but soon it turned to weeping;
137 for from the new land a whirlwind arose
138 and struck the bow of the ship.

139 Three times it made it whirl with all the waters;
140 at the fourth, it lifted the stern into the air
141 and sent the prow down, as pleased another,
